---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Newly Diagnosed with Mantle Cell Lymphoma | MCLA" description="A calm, step-by-step guide for people recently diagnosed with Mantle Cell Lymphoma — pathology explained, first-appointment tips, expert videos, and trusted resources.">

  <!-- BREADCRUMB -->
  <div class="nd-breadcrumb">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <a href="/">Home</a><span class="nd-sep">/</span>
      <a href="/understanding-mcl/what-is-mcl">Understanding MCL</a><span class="nd-sep">/</span>
      <span class="nd-current">Newly Diagnosed</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <header class="nd-hero">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <div class="nd-hero-grid">
        <div>
          <div class="nd-eyebrow">Start Here</div>
          <h1 class="nd-h1">Newly diagnosed with <span class="nd-t-teal">mantle cell</span> <span class="nd-t-amber">lymphoma?</span></h1>
          <p class="nd-lead">Hearing the words "Mantle Cell Lymphoma" can feel overwhelming. Take a breath — you do not need to understand everything today. Treatment for MCL has changed dramatically in recent years. There is real reason for hope, and you are in the right place.</p>
          <div class="nd-actions">
            <a href="#steps" class="nd-btn-primary">Start with the 7-step guide →</a>
            <a href="/understanding-mcl/find-specialist" class="nd-btn-outline">Find an MCL specialist</a>
          </div>
        </div>
        <aside class="nd-hero-card">
          <h3>How to use this page</h3>
          <div class="nd-reassure">
            <div class="nd-dot">1</div>
            <p>Work through the seven steps at your own pace.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="nd-reassure">
            <div class="nd-dot">2</div>
            <p>Bookmark the page. Most patients come back over days and weeks.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="nd-reassure">
            <div class="nd-dot">3</div>
            <p>Share it with your caregiver.</p>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- 7-STEP GUIDE -->
  <section id="steps" class="nd-section nd-section-panel">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <div class="nd-section-header">
        <div class="nd-eyebrow">Step-by-step guide</div>
        <h2 class="nd-h2">Seven steps to orient yourself after an MCL diagnosis</h2>
        <p class="nd-section-sub">A calm starting point — not a comprehensive textbook. Each step links to a dedicated section with deeper information, expert videos, and trusted resources.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="nd-step-grid">
        <a href="#understand" class="nd-step-card">
          <div class="nd-step-row"><div class="nd-step-icon">📋</div><div class="nd-step-num">Step 1</div></div>
          <h3 class="nd-step-h">Understand your diagnosis</h3>
          <p class="nd-step-p">Learn the basics of MCL: how it is diagnosed, staging, and the disease features your care team will discuss.</p>
          <span class="nd-step-link">Learn about MCL <span class="nd-arrow">→</span></span>
        </a>
        <a href="#testing" class="nd-step-card">
          <div class="nd-step-row"><div class="nd-step-icon">🧬</div><div class="nd-step-num">Step 2</div></div>
          <h3 class="nd-step-h">Understand your key tests</h3>
          <p class="nd-step-p">Pathology review, TP53, Ki-67, genetic testing, and imaging — and what each one tells your doctors.</p>
          <span class="nd-step-link">Important tests <span class="nd-arrow">→</span></span>
        </a>
        <a href="/understanding-mcl/find-specialist/" class="nd-step-card">
          <div class="nd-step-row"><div class="nd-step-icon">🩺</div><div class="nd-step-num">Step 3</div></div>
          <h3 class="nd-step-h">Find an MCL specialist</h3>
          <p class="nd-step-p">MCL is rare. Consulting a doctor who specialises in it — even once — can meaningfully shape your care plan.</p>
          <span class="nd-step-link">Find an MCL expert <span class="nd-arrow">→</span></span>
        </a>
        <a href="/understanding-mcl/treatment-options" class="nd-step-card">
          <div class="nd-step-row"><div class="nd-step-icon">💊</div><div class="nd-step-num">Step 4</div></div>
          <h3 class="nd-step-h">Learn about treatment options</h3>
          <p class="nd-step-p">Targeted therapies, immunotherapy, chemotherapy, CAR-T, bispecifics, and trials — the landscape is evolving fast.</p>
          <span class="nd-step-link">Explore treatment options <span class="nd-arrow">→</span></span>
        </a>
        <a href="#understand" class="nd-step-card">
          <div class="nd-step-row"><div class="nd-step-icon">🔬</div><div class="nd-step-num">Step 5</div></div>
          <h3 class="nd-step-h">Consider clinical trials</h3>
          <p class="nd-step-p">Trials drive progress in rare cancers and can offer access to promising therapies before they are widely available.</p>
          <span class="nd-step-link">Clinical trials <span class="nd-arrow">→</span></span>
        </a>
        <a href="#support" class="nd-step-card">
          <div class="nd-step-row"><div class="nd-step-icon">❤️</div><div class="nd-step-num">Step 6</div></div>
          <h3 class="nd-step-h">Build your support system</h3>
          <p class="nd-step-p">Caregivers, peer communities, and educational events. You do not have to face this alone.</p>
          <span class="nd-step-link">Support &amp; community <span class="nd-arrow">→</span></span>
        </a>
        <a href="#resources" class="nd-step-card nd-step-center">
          <div class="nd-step-row"><div class="nd-step-icon">📚</div><div class="nd-step-num">Step 7</div></div>
          <h3 class="nd-step-h">Explore the resource library</h3>
          <p class="nd-step-p">Educational guides, webinars with MCL experts, patient stories, and practical tools for navigating treatment.</p>
          <span class="nd-step-link">Resource library <span class="nd-arrow">→</span></span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- NCCN + VIDEOS -->
  <section id="understand" class="nd-section nd-section-white">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <div class="nd-section-header">
        <div class="nd-eyebrow">Expert Resources</div>
        <h2 class="nd-h2">Start with trusted, up-to-date information</h2>
        <p class="nd-section-sub">Three resources we recommend to almost every newly diagnosed patient and caregiver.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="nd-resource-feature">
        <div>
          <span class="nd-rf-badge">Recommended Guide</span>
          <h3 class="nd-rf-h">NCCN Guidelines for Patients<sup>®</sup>: Mantle Cell Lymphoma 2025</h3>
          <p class="nd-rf-p">A 56-page plain-language guide produced by the National Comprehensive Cancer Network® — a not-for-profit alliance of 34 leading cancer centres devoted to patient care, research, and education.</p>
        </div>
        <a href="https://www.nccn.org/patientresources/patient-resources/guidelines-for-patients/guidelines-for-patients-details?patientGuidelineId=20" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nd-btn-primary">Download the guide →</a>
      </div>

      <h3 class="nd-videos-h">Videos Worth Watching</h3>

      <div class="nd-video-grid">
        <a href="https://us06web.zoom.us/rec/play/D9WGAQwxO9F1wXxqP1RtpUYxwfBgMKSN06mLu2NImvnbIQHi5v4zDMuxvQ4cRY5mHJWhTfmjjHMYPJQN.t93YIRsUI2q61-HP?eagerLoadZvaPages=sidemenu.billing.plan_management&accessLevel=meeting&canPlayFromShare=true&from=share_recording_detail&startTime=1773084833000&oldStyle=true&pwd=DOlAmlY73KAubZ4ZAAAAIAAAAKJvGtqQpOsGl39LJqlZzC5eHobn2TH0c9X5vHcMNewaCnSPkZkUIa1pxv4W6VaW2jAwMDAwNA&componentName=rec-play&originRequestUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fus06web.zoom.us%2Frec%2Fshare%2F5Zq-YI0whUqdIACO2W0-Y7rREqOyXU-bB5zg1DPRjkLgKtds_kAgDhFsWehfGANp.nTqL5h_cyxc7Mdyi%3FstartTime%3D1773084833000%26pwd%3DDOlAmlY73KAubZ4ZAAAAIAAAAKJvGtqQpOsGl39LJqlZzC5eHobn2TH0c9X5vHcMNewaCnSPkZkUIa1pxv4W6VaW2jAwMDAwNA" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nd-video-card">
          <div class="nd-video-thumb">
            <img src="/uploads/newly-diagnosed/kumar.png" alt="Dr. Anita Kumar — Initial Treatment for MCL 2026" />
            <div class="nd-stage-badge">Not yet in treatment</div>
            <div class="nd-play-btn"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M8 5v14l11-7z"/></svg></div>
            <div class="nd-duration">Zoom recording</div>
          </div>
          <div class="nd-video-body">
            <div class="nd-speaker">Dr. Anita Kumar · Memorial Sloan Kettering</div>
            <h3 class="nd-video-h">Initial Treatment for MCL 2026</h3>
            <div class="nd-meta">Watch this talk by <strong>Dr. Anita Kumar (Memorial Sloan Kettering)</strong>, recorded March 2026: Initial Treatment for MCL 2026. This is an excellent, accessible overview of front-line treatment options.</div>
            <span class="nd-watch">Watch the recording →</span>
          </div>
        </a>

        <a href="https://us06web.zoom.us/rec/play/DJVdnwiY8un7QtFkKT0ly7ZuDrjIioxoRrjtXKF1bR-teB2ahKi5pP43xHqh5pOY-S_OTSiy27-zvbn3.fAZxPnynWhku0vHi?accessLevel=meeting&canPlayFromShare=true&from=share_recording_detail&startTime=1741804489000&pwd=xtAInGIakwApQnotbbstytK3cHT2Jq3F&componentName=rec-play&originRequestUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fus06web.zoom.us%2Frec%2Fshare%2FallhvPrhYVXuuhfJtBZ1O0wUhUrIQYSD6zLiVWoClFbO6ONovaRpz0vRGd2JjK5t.ldplVzFFsgJcP7Ql%3FstartTime%3D1741804489000%26pwd%3DxtAInGIakwApQnotbbstytK3cHT2Jq3F" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nd-video-card">
          <div class="nd-video-thumb">
            <img src="/uploads/newly-diagnosed/wang.png" alt="Dr. Yucai Wang — Changes in Treatment & Treatment for High-Risk Patients" />
            <div class="nd-stage-badge nd-stage-teal">Already in treatment</div>
            <div class="nd-play-btn"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M8 5v14l11-7z"/></svg></div>
            <div class="nd-duration">Zoom recording</div>
          </div>
          <div class="nd-video-body">
            <div class="nd-speaker">Dr. Yucai Wang · Mayo Clinic</div>
            <h3 class="nd-video-h">Changes in Treatment &amp; Treatment for High-Risk Patients</h3>
            <div class="nd-meta">This more technical talk by <strong>Dr. Yucai Wang (Mayo Clinic)</strong>, recorded March 2025, summarizes the latest research presented at the 2024 American Society of Hematology conference.</div>
            <span class="nd-watch">Watch the recording →</span>
          </div>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PATHOLOGY DEEP-DIVE -->
  <section id="testing" class="nd-section nd-section-panel">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <div class="nd-section-header">
        <div class="nd-eyebrow">Step 2 · Deep dive</div>
        <h2 class="nd-h2">Understanding your pathology report</h2>
        <p class="nd-section-sub">After a biopsy confirms MCL, your doctor will receive a pathology report. The terminology can feel confusing — understanding a few key elements will help you feel more confident in conversations with your care team.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="nd-deep">
        <aside class="nd-toc">
          <h4>On this page</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="#confirming">Confirming MCL</a></li>
            <li><a href="#ki67">Ki-67 proliferation index</a></li>
            <li><a href="#tp53">TP53 mutation</a></li>
            <li><a href="#variants">MCL variants</a></li>
            <li><a href="#indolent">Indolent vs. nodal MCL</a></li>
            <li><a href="#staging">Staging</a></li>
            <li><a href="#second">Second pathology review</a></li>
            <li><a href="#questions">Questions to ask</a></li>
          </ul>
        </aside>

        <div class="nd-deep-content">
          <h3 id="confirming" class="nd-deep-h">Confirming Mantle Cell Lymphoma</h3>
          <p>Most MCL diagnoses are confirmed through a lymph node biopsy or tissue sample. Pathologists examine the sample under a microscope and run specialised testing for features unique to MCL. A hallmark of MCL is a genetic change involving the <span class="nd-term">cyclin D1</span> gene, often caused by a chromosomal translocation known as <span class="nd-term">t(11;14)</span>. This finding distinguishes MCL from other types of lymphoma.</p>

          <h3 id="ki67" class="nd-deep-h">Ki-67 proliferation index</h3>
          <p><span class="nd-term">Ki-67</span> measures how quickly lymphoma cells are dividing. A higher percentage generally indicates more rapidly growing disease. Your doctor may weigh this when considering treatment options.</p>

          <h3 id="tp53" class="nd-deep-h">TP53 mutation</h3>
          <p><span class="nd-term">TP53</span> is a gene that helps regulate how cells repair damage. When the gene is altered, lymphoma may behave more aggressively and respond differently to certain treatments. TP53 testing has become increasingly important in guiding treatment decisions.</p>

          <h3 id="variants" class="nd-deep-h">MCL variants</h3>
          <p>Your report may describe the appearance of the lymphoma cells under a microscope. Some variants include:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Classic MCL</strong> — the most common form.</li>
            <li><strong>Blastoid variant</strong> — often grows faster than classic MCL.</li>
            <li><strong>Pleomorphic variant</strong> — also considered more aggressive.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>These descriptions help doctors anticipate how the disease may behave.</p>

          <h3 id="indolent" class="nd-deep-h">Indolent vs. nodal MCL</h3>
          <div class="nd-callout">
            <div class="nd-callout-title">Why this distinction matters</div>
            <p>MCL can behave very differently from patient to patient. <strong>Indolent</strong> (leukemic, non-nodal) MCL tends to grow slowly and may not require immediate treatment. <strong>Nodal</strong> MCL is typically more aggressive and is often treated sooner. Ask your oncologist which pattern best describes your disease.</p>
          </div>

          <h3 id="staging" class="nd-deep-h">Staging</h3>
          <p>After diagnosis, tests such as PET scans, CT scans, or bone marrow biopsies help determine how widely the lymphoma has spread. Staging typically ranges from <span class="nd-term">Stage I</span> (limited to one area) to <span class="nd-term">Stage IV</span> (found in multiple sites including lymph nodes, bone marrow, blood, or organs). Most people with MCL are diagnosed at a later stage — but stage alone does not determine prognosis or treatment. Symptoms, Ki-67, TP53 status, and overall health are often just as important.</p>

          <h3 id="second" class="nd-deep-h">When to consider a second pathology review</h3>
          <p>Because MCL is rare, some patients choose to have their biopsy reviewed by a pathologist who specialises in lymphomas at a major cancer centre. This provides additional confidence in the diagnosis and ensures that all important markers have been evaluated.</p>

          <h3 id="questions" class="nd-deep-h">Questions you may want to ask</h3>
          <div class="nd-qcard">
            <div class="nd-q-title">Bring these to your next appointment</div>
            <ul>
              <li>What subtype of MCL do I have?</li>
              <li>What is my Ki-67 score?</li>
              <li>Was TP53 testing performed? What did it show?</li>
              <li>Is my disease considered indolent or nodal?</li>
              <li>Should my biopsy be reviewed by a lymphoma specialist?</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FIRST APPOINTMENT -->
  <section id="specialist" class="nd-section nd-section-white">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <div class="nd-section-header">
        <div class="nd-eyebrow">Step 3 · What to expect</div>
        <h2 class="nd-h2">What your first oncology appointment may be like</h2>
        <p class="nd-section-sub">The first visit is usually focused on understanding your diagnosis and discussing possible next steps — not on making every decision at once.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="nd-deep">
        <aside class="nd-toc">
          <h4>On this page</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="#preparing">Preparing for your visit</a></li>
            <li><a href="#during">What typically happens</a></li>
            <li><a href="#support-person">Bringing support</a></li>
            <li><a href="#ask">Questions to ask</a></li>
          </ul>
        </aside>

        <div class="nd-deep-content">
          <h3 id="preparing" class="nd-deep-h">Preparing for your first visit</h3>
          <p>Meeting with an oncologist after a cancer diagnosis can feel overwhelming. Many patients worry about what questions to ask, what decisions will be required, and what the future may hold. Give yourself permission to arrive with questions — not answers.</p>

          <h3 id="during" class="nd-deep-h">What typically happens during the appointment</h3>
          <p>Your doctor will usually begin by reviewing:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Your medical history</li>
            <li>The biopsy results</li>
            <li>Imaging scans</li>
            <li>Laboratory tests</li>
          </ul>
          <p>They may perform a physical exam and discuss any symptoms. During the visit, your oncologist may explain the type of MCL you have, whether treatment is recommended now or later, potential treatment options, and any additional testing that may be needed. <strong>Not all decisions need to be made during the first appointment.</strong></p>

          <h3 id="support-person" class="nd-deep-h">Bringing support</h3>
          <p>Many patients find it helpful to bring someone with them. A caregiver, spouse, family member, or friend can help take notes, remember information, and ask questions you may not think of in the moment. Two sets of ears can be incredibly helpful.</p>

          <h3 id="ask" class="nd-deep-h">Questions you may consider asking</h3>
          <div class="nd-qcard">
            <div class="nd-q-title">Worth asking at your first visit</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Do I need treatment right away?</li>
              <li>What treatment options are available?</li>
              <li>Should I consider a second opinion?</li>
              <li>Are clinical trials available for my situation?</li>
              <li>What is the best way to reach the care team between visits?</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p class="nd-italic">It is normal to leave the appointment with more questions than answers. That is part of the process.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMMUNITY BAND -->
  <section id="support" class="nd-community">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <div class="nd-eyebrow">Step 6 · Connect with others</div>
      <h2 class="nd-community-h">You do not have to face this alone</h2>
      <p class="nd-community-p">Many patients and caregivers find it invaluable to connect with others who understand what they're going through. Online MCL communities offer support, practical guidance, and a place to ask questions — some are even organised by treatment centre or location.</p>
      <a href="/get-involved/volunteer" class="nd-btn-amber">Find an MCL community →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- HELPFUL ORGS -->
  <section id="resources" class="nd-section">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <div class="nd-section-header">
        <div class="nd-eyebrow">Helpful organisations</div>
        <h2 class="nd-h2">Trusted nonprofits that serve the broader blood cancer community</h2>
        <p class="nd-section-sub">These organisations offer excellent resources beyond what MCLA publishes — and we work alongside many of them.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="nd-org-grid">
        <a href="https://bloodcancerunited.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nd-org-card">
          <div class="nd-org-logo-box">
            <img src="/uploads/newly-diagnosed/bcu-logo.jpeg" alt="Blood Cancer United" />
          </div>
          <div class="nd-org-desc">Patient support, education, advocacy and research funding across all blood cancers.</div>
          <span class="nd-org-link">Visit site →</span>
        </a>

        <a href="https://lymphoma.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nd-org-card">
          <div class="nd-org-logo-box nd-org-lrf">
            <img src="https://lymphoma.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/LRF_small_Lavender-White_RGB.svg" alt="Lymphoma Research Foundation" />
          </div>
          <div class="nd-org-desc">The largest nonprofit solely dedicated to funding lymphoma research and patient programs.</div>
          <span class="nd-org-link">Visit site →</span>
        </a>

        <a href="https://bmtinfonet.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nd-org-card">
          <div class="nd-org-logo-box nd-org-bmt">
            <div>bmt infonet</div>
            <div class="nd-org-bmt-acc">Blood &amp; Marrow Transplant</div>
          </div>
          <div class="nd-org-desc">Information on cellular therapies such as CAR-T and bone marrow transplant.</div>
          <span class="nd-org-link">Visit site →</span>
        </a>

        <a href="https://www.cancercare.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="nd-org-card">
          <div class="nd-org-logo-box">
            <img src="https://www.cancercare.org/images/logos/80-logo-final.png" alt="CancerCare" />
          </div>
          <div class="nd-org-desc">Free, professional support services for anyone affected by cancer.</div>
          <span class="nd-org-link">Visit site →</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CLOSING MESSAGE -->
  <section class="nd-closing">
    <div class="nd-container">
      <div class="nd-closing-inner">
        <div class="nd-qmark">"</div>
        <h2 class="nd-closing-h">If you are newly diagnosed with Mantle Cell Lymphoma, you may feel frightened, uncertain, or overwhelmed. Those feelings are normal. But there is also reason for hope.</h2>
        <p>In recent years, treatment advances for MCL have transformed what is possible, and research continues to move the field forward.</p>
        <p>Take things one step at a time. And know that a community of patients, caregivers, doctors, and researchers is working every day to improve outcomes for people living with this disease.</p>
        <div class="nd-attrib">— The Mantle Cell Lymphoma Alliance</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Scoped styles for /newly-diagnosed page */

  :root {
    --nd-cream: #fafaf8;
    --nd-teal: #0a6b6e;
    --nd-teal-light: #0e8488;
    --nd-teal-deep: #1a3a3c;
    --nd-amber: #d4864e;
    --nd-amber-soft: #e8a66a;
    --nd-text-dark: #1a2e30;
    --nd-text-mid: #4a6264;
    --nd-text-light: #7a9295;
    --nd-border: #e6e6e0;
    --nd-white: #ffffff;
    --nd-panel: #f2f2ec;
  }

  .nd-container { max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 1.5rem; }
  @media (min-width: 1024px) { .nd-container { padding: 0 3rem; } }

  /* Breadcrumb */
  .nd-breadcrumb { background: var(--nd-cream); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--nd-border); font-size: 13px; color: var(--nd-text-mid); padding: 0.85rem 0; }
  .nd-breadcrumb a { color: var(--nd-text-mid); font-weight: 500; text-decoration: none; }
  .nd-breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--nd-teal); }
  .nd-sep { margin: 0 0.5rem; color: var(--nd-text-light); }
  .nd-current { color: var(--nd-text-dark); font-weight: 600; }

  /* Hero */
  .nd-hero { background: var(--nd-cream); overflow: hidden; padding: 4rem 0 4.5rem; }
  @media (min-width: 768px) { .nd-hero { padding: 5rem 0 5.5rem; } }
  @media (min-width: 1024px) { .nd-hero { padding: 6rem 0 6rem; } }
  .nd-hero-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; align-items: center; }
  @media (min-width: 1024px) { .nd-hero-grid { grid-template-columns: 1.2fr 1fr; gap: 4rem; } }
  .nd-eyebrow { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 800; letter-spacing: 2px; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--nd-amber); margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
  .nd-h1 { font-size: clamp(2.25rem, 5.2vw, 3.5rem); font-weight: 900; line-height: 1.08; letter-spacing: -1.2px; color: var(--nd-text-dark); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .nd-t-teal { color: var(--nd-teal); }
  .nd-t-amber { color: var(--nd-amber); }
  .nd-lead { font-size: clamp(1.05rem, 1.8vw, 1.2rem); color: var(--nd-text-mid); line-height: 1.7; max-width: 540px; margin-bottom: 2.25rem; }
